3. The Unified Interaction Style Matrix (Level 3 &amp; 4)
The ARB mandates a strict binary split at the Interaction Style level. Developers must first
answer: &#39;Can the client afford to wait?&#39;
A. Synchronous (Blocking)
The consumer thread blocks and waits for an immediate response. Temporal coupling is
high.
 • RESTful (Request/Response): Real-time queries &amp; auth decisions. (Risk: Tight
coupling)
 • GraphQL (Federated API): Mobile/Web composite data (BFF). (Risk: Core query
overload)
 • gRPC / Protobuf: High-throughput internal East-West calls. (Risk: Binary, tooling
support)
 • API Façade / Anti-Corruption Layer: Semantic isolation of legacy cores.
B. Asynchronous (Non-Blocking)
The thread releases; processing happens later. Categorized by routing control:
1. B.1 Targeted (Commands - 1-to-1)
 • Message Queue (P2P): Guaranteed delivery. e.g., &#39;Execute Payment&#39;.
 • Saga / Choreography: Long-running distributed transactions spanning multiple
cores.
2. B.2 Broadcast (Event/Push - 1-to-Many)
 • Event Streaming (Kafka): &#39;Fact&#39; distribution. e.g., &#39;Account Opened&#39;.
 • Change Data Capture (CDC): Legacy DB changes published as events.
 • Webhooks: External push notifications to B2B partners.
3. B.3 Deferred (Pull/Batch - Consumer Driven)
 • Scheduled Batch / ETL: Legacy synchronization (EOD Ledger).
 • Claim Check / MFT: Massive payload retrieval (e.g., 2GB Loan Documents).

4. ARB Guardrails &amp; Legacy Containment
Strategic Paved Roads: Net-new integrations must utilize Broadcom Layer7 for edge
security, Kubernetes (Spring Boot/Go) for orchestration, and Kafka/IBM MQ for state
distribution. Teams following these paths receive expedited ARB approval.
Legacy Containment (TIBCO / MuleSoft): Older ESB platforms are strictly contained.
They are approved ONLY for existing legacy interactions and may not be utilized to
orchestrate net-new digital channel (Experience Layer) workflows.

5. Practical Application: Cross-Bank Transfer (M&amp;A)
How the framework defines a transfer between the Main Bank and an Acquired Bank Core:
 • L1 Boundary: East-West (Cross-Core)
 • L2 Layer: Process (Orchestration)
 • L3 Style: Asynchronous Targeted (Command)
 • L4 Pattern: Saga (To handle potential rollbacks across distributed ledgers)
 • L5 Protocol: AMQP
 • L6 Platform: K8s Worker + IBM MQ
